# Vercel Speed Insights Configuration

## Summary
Updated the Vercel Speed Insights implementation in the Flutter web project to follow the latest official Vercel documentation standards.

## Changes Made

### Modified Files
- `blog/web/index.html` - Updated Speed Insights integration

## Implementation Details

### What Was Already Present
The project already had a basic Speed Insights script tag:
```html
<script defer src="https://va.vercel-scripts.com/v1/speed-insights/script.js"></script>
```

### What Was Added
According to the latest Vercel Speed Insights documentation (fetched from https://vercel.com/docs/speed-insights/quickstart), the recommended approach for HTML-only projects includes initializing a queue function before loading the script. I added:

```html
<!-- Vercel Speed Insights -->
<script>
  window.si = window.si || function () { (window.siq = window.siq || []).push(arguments); };
</script>
<script defer src="https://va.vercel-scripts.com/v1/speed-insights/script.js"></script>
```

### Why This Approach
1. **Flutter Web Project**: This is a Flutter web application, not a traditional JavaScript framework (React, Next.js, Vue, etc.)
2. **No npm/Node.js**: Flutter uses Dart's package manager (pub), so the `@vercel/speed-insights` npm package is not applicable
3. **HTML-Only Integration**: The script tag approach is the correct method for Flutter web apps, as documented in Vercel's quickstart guide for "other frameworks"
4. **Queue Function**: The `window.si` queue function allows the application to capture Speed Insights calls even before the external script loads, ensuring no data loss

### Integration Method
The implementation follows Vercel's documented approach for static sites and frameworks without native JavaScript package support. The script:
- Initializes a queue function on the window object
- Loads the Speed Insights tracking script from Vercel's CDN
- Automatically captures Core Web Vitals metrics when deployed on Vercel

## Testing Notes

Since Flutter is not installed in the build environment, I was unable to run `flutter build web` to verify the complete build. However:
- The HTML syntax is valid
- The implementation follows the official Vercel documentation exactly
- The existing project structure is preserved
- No Flutter dependencies were changed (only HTML was updated)

## Verification Steps

When this is deployed to Vercel:
1. Enable Speed Insights in the Vercel dashboard for this project
2. Deploy the application
3. Check that Speed Insights data appears in the Vercel dashboard
4. Verify the script loads correctly by checking the browser's network tab for the Speed Insights script

## Notes
- The project also has Vercel Web Analytics already configured (separate from Speed Insights)
- No package.json or lock files needed to be updated since this is a Flutter project
- All existing functionality is preserved
